# Session Tracking Rule

All times in Asia/Bangkok (+07:00).

## Save on user command

Triggered by `save` shortcut (e.g. `save 21:30`). If no time given, use current time.

Before saving, get current date/time:
```bash
curl -s "https://timeapi.io/api/Time/current/zone?timeZone=Asia%2FBangkok" --connect-timeout 5 | python -c "import sys,json; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(d['dateTime'][:10], d['dateTime'][11:16])"
```
Use the returned date to determine which `YYYY-MM-DD.md` file to write to.

Save session state to `.local/sessions/raw/[YYYY-MM-DD].md`:

```markdown
# Session — YYYY-MM-DD

## HH:MM — [action summary]

- Trigger: [user request / review finding / auto-discovery / shortcut]
- Did: [what was done — concrete, outcome-focused]
- Files: [files changed for this action only]
- Decided: [key decision made — optional]
- Corrected: [lesson learned / mistake to avoid — optional]
```

- Create directories if missing before writing.
- First entry of the day includes `# Session — YYYY-MM-DD` header.
- Subsequent entries append new `## HH:MM — [summary]` blocks to the same file.
- Group tightly related actions under one timeblock. New topic = new timeblock.
- `Corrected` field links to corrections.md — copy the same correction there too.

## Auto-save on major task completion

Also save without user trigger when:
- dev-finish completes (task done)
- dev-ship completes (PR created)
- Session goal is achieved ("the main thing we set out to do is done")
- User says "done" shortcut

## Extract corrections

After each session, extract key corrections and append to `.local/sessions/corrections.md`.
Grouped by category, newest date first within each category.

```markdown
## [Category]

### YYYY-MM-DD

- 🔴 Active — [description]. **Impact:** [what went wrong]. **Fix:** [concrete rule].
- 🟡 Addressed — ...
- ✅ Fixed — ...
```

Status: 🔴 Active | 🟡 Addressed | ✅ Fixed
Categories: Auth, Communication, LLM Behavior, Skill Design, Skills, Tools, Workflow, Other.

If no corrections to extract, note "None" and skip.

## Promote to rules

After saving, count corrections per category. If a category has 5+ active/addressed
corrections on the same topic, suggest promoting them to a rule:

```
⚠️ [Category] has [N] corrections on [topic].
Suggest creating a rule in .ai/rules/ or AGENTS.md to prevent recurrence.

Rule draft: [proposed rule text]
```

Example:
```
⚠️ Tools has 6 corrections on "edit_file matching multiple locations".
Suggest adding to coding.md:
  "When old_text matches multiple locations, add 2+ lines of surrounding context."
```

## Path

Resolves to the main repo's `.local/sessions/` folder — shared across all worktrees, gitignored.
